<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathem=
atics">mathematics</a>, the <b>derivative</b> is a fundamental tool that qu=
antifies the sensitivity to change of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Function_(mathematics)" title=3D"Function (mathematics)">function</a>=
's output with respect to its input. The derivative of a function of a sing=
le variable at a chosen input value, when it exists, is the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slope" title=3D"Slope">slope</a> of the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tangent" title=3D"Tangent">tangent line</=
a> to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_of_a_function" tit=
le=3D"Graph of a function">graph of the function</a> at that point. The tan=
gent line is the best <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_appro=
ximation" title=3D"Linear approximation">linear approximation</a> of the fu=
nction near that input value. The derivative is often described as the <b>i=
nstantaneous rate of change</b>, the ratio of the instantaneous change in t=
he dependent variable to that of the independent variable.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-FOOTNOTEApostol1967160Stewart2002129=E2=80=93130Strang_et_al.2023[httpso=
penstaxorgbookscalculus-volume-1pages3-1-defining-the-derivative_224]_1-0" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derivative#cit=
e_note-FOOTNOTEApostol1967160Stewart2002129%E2%80%93130Strang_et_al.2023[ht=
tpsopenstaxorgbookscalculus-volume-1pages3-1-defining-the-derivative_224]-1=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> The process of finding a derivative is called <b>differentiati=
on</b>.
</p><p>There are multiple different <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Mathematical_notation" title=3D"Mathematical notation">notations</a> for =
differentiation. <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leibniz_notati=
on" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Leibniz notation">Leibniz notation</a></=
i>, named after <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gottfried_Wilhelm_=
Leibniz" title=3D"Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz">Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz</a>,=
 is represented as the ratio of two <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Differential_(mathematics)" title=3D"Differential (mathematics)">differen=
tials</a>, whereas <i>prime notation</i> is written by adding a <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_mark" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pr=
ime mark">prime mark</a>. Higher order notations represent repeated differe=
ntiation, and they are usually denoted in Leibniz notation by adding supers=
cripts to the differentials, and in prime notation by adding additional pri=
me marks. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Higher_order_derivative"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Higher order derivative">Higher order deriv=
atives</a> are used in physics; for example, the first derivative  with res=
pect to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Time" title=3D"Time">time<=
/a> of the position of a moving object is its <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Velocity" title=3D"Velocity">velocity</a>, and the second deriv=
ative is its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acceleration" title=
=3D"Acceleration">acceleration</a>.
</p><p>Derivatives can be generalized to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Function_of_several_real_variables" title=3D"Function of several rea=
l variables">functions of several real variables</a>. In this case, the der=
ivative is reinterpreted as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Line=
ar_transformation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Linear transformation">li=
near transformation</a> whose graph is (after an appropriate translation) t=
he best linear approximation to the graph of the original function. The <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacobian_matrix" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Jacobian matrix">Jacobian matrix</a> is the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_(mathematics)" title=3D"Matrix (mathematics)">m=
atrix</a> that represents this linear transformation with respect to the ba=
sis given by the choice of independent and dependent variables.  It can be =
calculated in terms of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partial=
_derivative" title=3D"Partial derivative">partial derivatives</a> with resp=
ect to the independent variables.  For a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Real-valued_function" title=3D"Real-valued function">real-valued fun=
ction</a> of several variables, the Jacobian matrix reduces to the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gradient_vector" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Gradient vector">gradient vector</a>.
</p>
