7=E2=80=93238]_13-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Derivative#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGonick2012156Thomas_et_al.2014114Strang=
_et_al.2023[httpsopenstaxorgbookscalculus-volume-1pages3-2-the-derivative-a=
s-a-function_237%E2%80%93238]-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Most functions that occur in practice have derivatives at all points=
 or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Almost_everywhere" title=3D"Al=
most everywhere">almost every</a> point. Early in the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_calculus" title=3D"History of calculus">hist=
ory of calculus</a>, many mathematicians assumed that a continuous function=
 was differentiable at most points.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEJa=C5=A1ek19=
22Jarn=C3=ADk1922Rychl=C3=ADk1923_14-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derivative#cite_note-FOOTNOTEJa%C5%A1ek1922Jarn%C=
3%ADk1922Rychl%C3%ADk1923-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Under mild conditions (for exampl=
e, if the function is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monotone_f=
unction" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Monotone function">monotone</a> or =
a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lipschitz_function" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Lipschitz function">Lipschitz function</a>), this is tru=
e. However, in 1872, Weierstrass found the first example of a function that=
 is continuous everywhere but differentiable nowhere.  This example is now =
known as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weierstrass_function"=
 title=3D"Weierstrass function">Weierstrass function</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-FOOTNOTEDavid2018_15-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Derivative#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavid2018-15"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In 1931,=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stefan_Banach" title=3D"Stefan Ba=
nach">Stefan Banach</a> proved that the set of functions that have a deriva=
tive at some point is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meager_set=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Meager set">meager set</a> in the space of=
 all continuous functions. Informally, this means that hardly any random co=
ntinuous functions have a derivative at even one point.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derivative=
#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
