yAbbenaSalamon2006[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidowEj9TMYo7ICpgPA826_826]-51"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup></li>
<li>Differentiation can also be defined for maps between <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_space" title=3D"Vector space">vector space</a=
>, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Banach_space" title=3D"=
Banach space">Banach space</a>, in which those generalizations are the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gateaux_derivative" title=3D"Gateaux d=
erivative">Gateaux derivative</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Fr%C3%A9chet_derivative" title=3D"Fr=C3=A9chet derivative">Fr=C3=A9=
chet derivative</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-52" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derivative#cite_note-52"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>52<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>One deficiency of the classical derivative is that very many functions =
are not differentiable. Nevertheless, there is a way of extending the notio=
n of the derivative so that all <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Co=
ntinuous_function" title=3D"Continuous function">continuous</a> functions a=
nd many other functions can be differentiated using a concept known as the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weak_derivative" title=3D"Weak der=
ivative">weak derivative</a>. The idea is to embed the continuous functions=
 in a larger space called the space of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Distribution_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Distributio=
n (mathematics)">distributions</a> and only require that a function is diff=
erentiable "on average".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFunaro1992[httpsbooksgo=
oglecombooksidCX4SXf3mdeUCpgPA84_84=E2=80=9385]_53-0" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derivative#cite_note-FOOTNOTEFunaro=
1992[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidCX4SXf3mdeUCpgPA84_84%E2%80%9385]-53"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup></li>
<li>Properties of the derivative have inspired the introduction and study o=
f many similar objects in algebra and topology; an example is <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_algebra" title=3D"Differential alg=
ebra">differential algebra</a>. Here, it consists of the derivation of some=
 topics in abstract algebra, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Ring_(mathematics)" title=3D"Ring (mathematics)">rings</a>, <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ideal_(ring_theory)" title=3D"Ideal (ring theo=
ry)">ideals</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_(mathematic=
s)" title=3D"Field (mathematics)">field</a>, and so on.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
FOOTNOTEKolchin1973[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidyDCfhIjka-8CpgPA58_58],_[http=
sbooksgooglecombooksidyDCfhIjka-8CpgPA126_126]_54-0" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derivative#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKolchin=
1973[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidyDCfhIjka-8CpgPA58_58],_[httpsbooksgooglecom=
booksidyDCfhIjka-8CpgPA126_126]-54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>The discrete equivalent of differentiation is <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Finite_difference" title=3D"Finite difference">finite diffe=
rences</a>. The study of differential calculus is unified with the calculus=
 of finite differences in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Time_sca=
le_calculus" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Time scale calculus">time scale=
 calculus</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGeorgiev2018[httpsbooksgooglecomb=
ooksidOJJVDwAAQBAJpgPA8_8]_55-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Derivative#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGeorgiev2018[httpsbooksgoog=
lecombooksidOJJVDwAAQBAJpgPA8_8]-55"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5=
5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic_derivative" tit=
le=3D"Arithmetic derivative">arithmetic derivative</a> involves the functio=
n that is defined for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer"=
 title=3D"Integer">integers</a> by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Prime_factorization" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Prime factorizatio=
n">prime factorization</a>. This is an analogy with the product rule.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBarbeau1961_56-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derivative#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBarbeau1961-56"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>56<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup></li></ul>
